# gen191 — F5 edit, a SECOND transformation. Rename (gen187) proved the
# locate -> edit -> compile-verify micro-loop; delete reuses the SAME loop with a
# different transformation rule (cut the top-level definition through its matching
# brace), showing the edit loop is rule-shaped, not a single hardcoded operation.
# The original file is never touched (temp-only); the verdict comes from the real
# compiler, not a guess (CODE-MASTERY.md §4).
#expect: pass
#faculty: edit-delete
# Under a DIRECTORY: locate the defining file first (F4 chained into F5).
> delete the function square under tests/code
< Deleted square in fixtures/sample.c; the result still compiles.
# By explicit file path; the whole definition (signature + balanced body) goes.
> remove the function add from tests/code/fixtures/sample.c
< Deleted add; the result still compiles.
# Comment-aware: the deletion skips a doc comment's stray "if (" / braces and
# removes the right region, leaving a translation unit that still compiles.
> remove the function twice from tests/code/fixtures/withcomment.c
< Deleted twice; the result still compiles.
# Honest decline when nothing under the directory defines the function.
> delete the function nope under tests/code
< I looked through tests/code but found no file that defines nope.
# Bilingual: Italian cue words reach the SAME edit loop (elimina/funzione).
> elimina la funzione square in tests/code/fixtures/sample.c
< Deleted square; the result still compiles.
